12. SECURITY ARCHITECTURE

12.1 Threat Model

```
ADVERSARY CAPABILITIES:
• Physical Access: Limited (space environment provides natural barrier)
• Remote Access: Full spectrum (RF, optical, quantum)
• Computational Resources: Nation-state level (including quantum computers)
• Timeframe: Multi-decade attacks possible

ATTACK VECTORS:
• Communication Interception: Eavesdropping, jamming, spoofing
• Computational Attacks: Cryptographic breaking, side channels
• Physical Attacks: Radiation-induced faults, laser dazzling
• Supply Chain: Hardware trojans, compromised components
• Insider Threats: Malicious AI, compromised ground stations
```

12.2 Security Controls

```
CRYPTOGRAPHIC SUITE:
• Symmetric: AES-256-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305
• Asymmetric (Classical): RSA-4096, ECC-521
• Asymmetric (Post-Quantum): CRYSTALS-Kyber (KEM), CRYSTALS-Dilithium (signatures)
• Hash Functions: SHA-3, SHAKE256
• Key Exchange: Quantum Key Distribution (unconditional security)
• Random Number Generation: Quantum random number generators (QRNG)

ACCESS CONTROL:
• Authentication: Multi-factor (biometric, cryptographic, behavioral)
• Authorization: Attribute-based with temporal constraints
• Audit: Immutable log with quantum-proof signatures
• Least Privilege: Microservices with minimal permissions

NETWORK SECURITY:
• Segmentation: Zero-trust architecture with encrypted east-west traffic
• Firewall: Stateful inspection with deep packet inspection
• Intrusion Detection: ML-based anomaly detection with quantum enhancement
• Honeypots: Decoy systems with entanglement-based triggers

PHYSICAL SECURITY:
• Tamper Detection: Quantum seals (entangled photon pairs)
• Secure Boot: Hardware root of trust with PUF (Physical Unclonable Function)
• Radiation Hardening: Protection against fault injection attacks
• Self-Destruct: Quantum erasure of sensitive data
```

12.3 Quantum Security Features

```
QUANTUM KEY DISTRIBUTION (QKD):
• Protocols: BB84 (decoy state), E91 (entanglement-based), TF-QKD (twin-field)
• Key Rate: 100 kbps at 1000 km distance
• Security Proof: Information-theoretic (unconditional)
• Implementation: Device-independent where possible

QUANTUM RANDOM NUMBER GENERATION:
• Source: Quantum vacuum fluctuations, photon arrival times
• Rate: 100 Gbps per generator
• Entropy: >0.999 per bit (verified by Bell tests)
• Certification: NIST SP 800-90B compliance

QUANTUM-SAFE CRYPTOGRAPHY:
• Lattice-based: CRYSTALS suite (Kyber, Dilithium, Saber)
• Hash-based: SPHINCS+
• Code-based: Classic McEliece
• Multivariate: Rainbow
• Implementation: Hybrid mode (classical + post-quantum)

QUANTUM NETWORK SECURITY:
• Entanglement Verification: Bell inequality tests
• Device-Independent: Security without trusting devices
• Quantum Digital Signatures: Information-theoretic signatures
• Quantum Money: Unforgeable currency for resource allocation
```

